## Commit: Integration of Biomedical Datasets and APIs for Drug Discovery Pipeline

### Overview

This commit incorporates multiple authoritative biomedical data sources to support the development of a scalable data analytics and machine learning pipeline for drug discovery. The integration enables access to chemical, biological, and pharmacological data required for downstream modelling and analysis.

---

### Data Sources

1. ChEMBL API
   https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chembl/api/data/docs

* Provides curated bioactivity data for drug-like compounds
* Includes molecules, targets, assays, and activity metrics
* Supports REST-based querying for dynamic data retrieval

2. STRING Database (Protein–Protein Interactions)
   https://string-db.org/cgi/download?sessionId=bWAilGSjQa6V

* Contains protein–protein interaction networks
* Enables graph-based analysis and biological pathway exploration

3. Drug Classification Dataset (Kaggle)
   https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/prathamtripathi/drug-classification

* Structured dataset for supervised classification tasks
* Includes patient attributes and corresponding drug labels

4. Drug Discovery / Virtual Screening Dataset (Kaggle)
   https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/shahriarkabir/drug-discovery-virtual-screening-dataset

* Provides molecular descriptors and screening outcomes
* Suitable for predictive modelling and candidate prioritisation

5. ChEMBL Dataset (BigQuery / Kaggle)
   https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/bigquery/ebi-chembl

* Large-scale dataset derived from ChEMBL
* Supports distributed data processing and analytics

---

### Technical Integration

* API-based data ingestion (ChEMBL REST endpoints)
* Batch processing of structured datasets (Kaggle sources)
* Integration of graph data (STRING PPI networks)
* Data preprocessing: cleaning, transformation, and normalisation

---

### Intended Applications

* Drug classification and prediction models
* Drug–target interaction analysis
* Network-based modelling using protein interaction data
* Support for scalable analytics frameworks (e.g., Spark)

---

### Significance

This integration establishes a unified data foundation combining chemical, biological, and clinical perspectives. It enables the development of robust, data-driven models aligned with contemporary drug discovery workflows.

